To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LATEX, we can use the `pgf` and `tikz` packages which provide powerful tools for creating graphics and diagrams.

First, we need to parse the FEN notation into a set of piece positions that we can use to draw the board. For simplicity, let's assume that the FEN notation is stored in a variable called `\fen`.

Next, we define a macro `\drawboard` that takes the FEN notation as an argument and uses `tikz` to draw the chessboard. Here's the LATEX code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{pgf}

% Define a macro to draw the chessboard
\newcommand{\drawboard}[1]{
  % Parse the FEN notation into a set of piece positions
  % (This step is not shown in this code snippet)

  % Set up the dimensions and style of the chessboard
  \pgfmathsetmacro{\cellsize}{2cm}
  \pgfmathsetmacro{\boardsize}{\cellsize*8}
  \tikzstyle{cell} = [draw, minimum size=\cellsize, inner sep=0]

  % Draw the chessboard squares
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \foreach \x in {1,...,8} {
      \foreach \y in {1,...,8} {
        \node[cell] at (\x-\y/2,\y/2) {};
      }
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}

  % Add the chess pieces to the board (based on the FEN notation)
  % (This step is not shown in this code snippet)
}

% Define a variable to hold the FEN notation
\newcommand{\fen}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

% Draw the chessboard using the FEN notation
\drawboard{\fen}
```

In this code, the `\drawboard` macro sets up a `tikzpicture` environment and uses nested loops to draw the chessboard squares. The dimensions of the board are controlled by the `\cellsize` and `\boardsize` variables.

