In Java, you should use the `.equals()` method to compare the values of strings, rather than the `==` operator.

The `==` operator checks if two objects have the same reference in memory, meaning it checks if they are literally the same object. In the case of strings, this means that the `==` operator checks if two variables reference the same string object in memory.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method checks if the values of two strings are equal, regardless of whether they are stored in the same or different string objects in memory.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";

if (str1 == str2) {
    // This will not execute because str1 and str2 have different references
    System.out.println("The strings are equal (using ==)");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    // This will execute because str1 and str2 have the same value
    System.out.println("The strings are equal (using equals())");
}
```

In this example, `str1` and `str2` have the same value, but they are stored in different string objects in memory, so the `==` operator will not consider them equal. However, the `.equals()` method will consider them equal because they have the same value.

In general, you should use the `.equals()` method to compare the values of strings, and reserve the `==` operator for comparing primitive values such as `int`, `float`, or `boolean`.

